{"parse":{"title":"hi","pageid":4804,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"hi\"}}\n{{minitoc}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{clip|mul|en:'''Hi'''ndi}}, from {{der|mul|hi|हिन्दी|tr='''hi'''ndī}}, from {{der|mul|fa-cls|هِنْدِی|tr='''hi'''ndī}}.\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|1}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n[[American English]]. First recorded reference is to speech of a Kansas Indian (1862); originally to attract attention, probably a variant of {{inh|en|enm|hey}}, {{m|enm|hy}} ([[circa]] 1475). Also an exclamation to call attention. See {{m|en|hey}}.{{rfref|en}}\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|en|heigh}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/haɪ/}}, {{rhymes|en|aɪ|s=1}}\n** {{homophones|en|Hi|hie|high}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-hi.ogg|a=US}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-hi.ogg|a=UK}}\n* {{IPA|en|/haːj/|a=Indic}}\n\n====Interjection====\n{{en-intj}}\n\n# {{n-g|A [[friendly]], [[informal]], [[casual]] [[greeting]] said upon someone's [[arrival]].}}\n#: {{syn|en|hello|greetings|howdy}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Hi''', how are you?}}\n#: {{ux|en|I just dropped by to say “'''hi'''”.}}\n#* '''2016''', [https://web.archive.org/web/20170925022505/https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/lets-learn-english-lesson-4/3168920.html VOA Learning English] (public domain)\n#*: Anna: Pete, hi! Hi, we are here! &mdash; Pete: Hi, Anna! Hi, Marsha!  &mdash; Anna: Hi!  &mdash; Pete: How are you two?  &mdash; Marsha: I am great!\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1862|author=Miriam Davis Colt|title=Went to Kansas|url=http://www.kancoll.org/books/colt/|page=143|publisher=L. Ingalls & Company|isbn=9780608429793|pageurl=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Went_to_Kansas/OVQDAAAAYAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=%22hi%22+kansas&pg=PA143&printsec=frontcover|text=When out on the prairie, up galloped an Indian on his pony with his saluting \"'''hi'''!\"}}\n# {{n-g|An [[exclamation]] to call attention.}}\n#* {{RQ:Lincoln Pratt's Patients|chapter=7|passage=I made a speaking trumpet of my hands and commenced to whoop “Ahoy!” and “Hello!” at the top of my lungs. {{...}} The Colonel woke up, and, after asking what in brimstone was the matter, opened his mouth and roared “'''Hi!'''” and “Hello!” like the bull of Bashan.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1954|author=J. R. R. Tolkien|title=The Two Towers|passage='Come back now!' shouted Sam. ''''Hi'''! Come back!' But Gollum had vanished.}}\n# {{lb|en|dated outside of Ireland}} {{n-g|Expressing [[wonder]] or [[derision]].}}\n#: {{ux|en|How did he do that, '''hi'''?}}\n#: {{ux|en|That’s mad, '''hi'''!}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|en|hi there|hi-bye friend|bonjour/hi|rehi}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n{{top4}}\n* {{desc|tpi|hai}}\n* {{desc|zh|嗨|hi|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|de|hi|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|hi|हेलो|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|is|hæ|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ms|hai|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ml|ഹായ്|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|vi|hai|bor=1}}\n{{bottom}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|friendly, informal greeting}}\n{{multitrans|data=\n* Afrikaans: {{tt+|af|haai}}\n* Aleut: {{tt|ale|aang}}\n* Altai:\n*: Southern Altai: {{tt|alt|эзен}}\n* Alutiiq: {{t|ems|cama’i}}\n* Ambonese Malay: {{tt|abs|oe}}\n* American Sign Language: {{tt|ase|B@Sfhead-PalmForward B@FromSfhead-PalmForward}}\n* Amharic: {{tt|am|ሰላም}}\n* Arabic: {{tt+|ar|مَرْحَبًا}}, {{tt+|ar|سَلَام}}, {{tt+|ar|أَهْلًا}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{tt|arz|أهلاً}}\n*: Gulf Arabic: {{t|afb|هلا|tr=hala}}, {{t|afb|قوة|tr=guwa}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{tt|acw|هلا|tr=hala}}, {{tt|acw|مَرْحَبَا|tr=marḥaba}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{tt|ary|السلام|tr=s-salām}}\n* Armenian: {{tt+|hy|բարև}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|ei}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{tt+|az|salam}}\n* Bashkir: {{tt|ba|сәләм}}\n* Basque: {{tt+|eu|kaixo}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt|be|прыве́т}}, {{tt|be|здаро́ў}}\n* Bengali: {{tt+|bn|সালাম|tr=salam}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|здра́сти}}, {{tt+|bg|здраве́й}}\n* Burmese: {{tt+|my|မင်္ဂလာပါ}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|hola}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{tt|yue|你好|tr=nei5 hou2}}\n*: Dungan: {{tt|dng|сэляму}}\n*: Eastern Min: {{tt|cdo|汝好}}\n*: Hakka: {{tt|hak|你好|tr=ngì-hó}}\n*: Hokkien: {{tt|nan-hbl|你好|tr=lí hó}}\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|你好|tr=nǐ hǎo}} {{qualifier|the most common}}, {{tt+|cmn|嗨|tr=hāi}} {{tt+|cmn|哈囉|tr=hāluō}} {{qualifier|slang}}\n*: Wu: {{tt|wuu|儂好}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|ahoj}}, {{tt+|cs|čau}}, {{tt+|cs|čus}}, {{tt+|cs|nazdar}}, {{tt+|cs|zdar}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|hallo}}, {{tt+|da|hej|alt=hej!}}, {{tt+|da|dav}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|hallo}}, {{tt+|nl|hoi}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt+|eo|saluton}}, {{tt+|eo|sal}}\n* Estonian: {{tt+|et|hei}}, {{tt+|et|tere}}, {{tt|et|tervist}}\n* Faroese: {{tt|fo|hey}}, {{tt|fo|halló}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|hei}}, {{tt+|fi|moi}}, {{tt+|fi|terve}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|salut}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|ola}}\n* Georgian: {{tt+|ka|გამარჯობა}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|hallo}}, {{tt|de|'n Tag}}\n*: Alemannic German: {{t|gsw|sali}}, {{t|gsw|hoi}}, {{t|gsw|grüezi}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|γεια}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|שָׁלוֹם|tr=shalóm}}, {{tt+|he|היי|tr=haj}}\n* Hindi: {{tt+|hi|नमस्ते}}, {{tt+|hi|सलाम}} {{qualifier|used by Muslims}}, {{tt+|hi|हाइ}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|szia}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|halló}}, {{tt+|is|hæ}}\n* Indonesian: {{tt+|id|hai}}, {{tt+|id|salam}}\n* Interlingua: {{tt+|ia|salute}}, {{tt|ia|hallo}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|haigh}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|ciao}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|こんにちは|tr=konnichi wa}}, {{tt+|ja|やあ|tr=yā}}, {{tt+|ja|どうも|tr=dōmo}}, {{tt+|ja|よう|tr=yō}}\n* Kazakh: {{tt|kk|сәлем}}, {{tt|kk|салам}}\n* Khmer: {{tt|km|សួស្តី}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|안녕(安寧)}}\n* Krio: {{tt|kri|kusheh}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{tt+|kmr|merheba}}, {{tt+|kmr|silav}}, {{tt+|kmr|selam}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{tt+|ky|салам}}\n* Lao: {{tt+|lo|ສະບາຍດີ}}, {{tt|lo|ເຮີຍ}}\n* Latin: {{tt+|la|salve}}, {{tt+|la|ave}}\n* Latvian: {{qualifier|gender depending on the listener(s)}} {{tt+|lv|sveiks|m}}, {{tt|lv|sveika|f}}, {{tt|lv|sveiki|m-p}}, {{tt|lv|sveikas|f-p}}\n* Lithuanian: {{tt+|lt|labas}}, {{tt+|lt|sveikas}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|здраво}}\n* Malay: {{tt+|ms|hai}}, {{tt+|ms|salam}}\n* Maltese: {{tt|mt|ejj}}\n* Mansi:\n*: Eastern Mansi: {{t|mns-eas|пяся}}\n*: Northern Mansi: {{t|mns-nor|паща}}, {{t|mns-nor|пася}}\n*: Southern Mansi: {{t|mns-nor|tr=piśėn}}\n* Mongolian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt+|mn|сайн уу?}} {{q|informal}}, {{tt+|mn|сайн байна уу?}}\n* Nepali: {{tt+|ne|हाइ}} {{tt+|ne|नमस्कार}}, {{tt+|ne|नमस्ते}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt+|nb|hei}}, {{tt|nb|heisan}}\n* Occitan: {{tt+|oc|adieu}}\n* Ojibwe: {{tt|oj|boozhoo}}\n* Ossetian: {{tt|os|салам}}, {{tt|os|арфӕ}}\n* Pashto: {{tt+|ps|سلام|tr=salām}}\n* Persian:\n*: Iranian Persian: {{tt|fa-ira|سَلام}}, {{tt|fa-ira|دُرود}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|cześć}}, {{tt+|pl|hej}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|olá}}, {{tt+|pt|oi}}, {{tt+|pt|alô}}, {{tt+|pt|e aí|alt=e ai?}}\n* Punjabi: (''sat sri akal'', formal), (''kiddhan'', informal)\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|bună}}, {{tt+|ro|salut}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|приве́т}}, {{tt+|ru|здоро́во}}, {{tt+|ru|здра́сте}}\n* Sami:\n*: Inari Sami: {{tt|smn|tiervâ}}\n*: Northern Sami: {{tt|se|dearvva}}, {{tt|se|bures}}\n*: Skolt Sami: {{tt|sms|tiõrv}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|hòigh}}, {{t|gd|shin thu}} {{qualifier|informal and singular}}, {{t|gd|shin sibh}} {{qualifier|plural or formal}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|ћа̑о}}, {{tt|sh|здра̏во}}, {{tt|sh|ме̏рха̄ба}}, {{tt|sh|ха̀ло}}, {{tt|sh|бок}}\n*: Latin: {{tt|sh|ćȃo}}, {{tt+|sh|zdrȁvo}}, {{tt|sh|mȅrhāba}}, {{tt+|sh|hàlo}}, {{tt+|sh|bok}}\n* Sicilian: {{tt|scn|sabbinirìca}}\n* Slovak: {{tt+|sk|ahoj}}, {{tt|sk|čau}}, {{tt|sk|nazdar}}\n* Slovene: {{tt|sl|žívjo}}, {{tt|sl|zdrávo}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|hola}}\n* Sranan Tongo: {{tt|srn|fa}}, {{tt|srn|ofa}}\n* Swahili: {{tt+|sw|jambo}}, {{tt|sw|salaam}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|hallå}}, {{tt+|sv|hej|alt=hej!}}, {{tt+|sv|hejsan}}, {{tt+|sv|tja}}, {{tt+|sv|tjena}}\n* Tagalog: {{tt|tl|helo}}, {{tt+|tl|hoy}}\n* Tajik: {{tt|tg|салом}}\n* Tamil: {{tt+|ta|வணக்கம்}}\n* Tatar: {{tt+|tt|сәлам}}\n* Thai: {{tt|th|หวัดดี}}, {{tt+|th|สวัสดี}}\n* Tigrinya: {{tt|ti|ሰላም}}\n* Tok Pisin: {{tt|tpi|gude}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|merhaba}}, {{tt+|tr|selam}}\n* Turkmen: {{tt|tk|salam}}\n* Tz'utujil: {{tt|tzj|coli}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt+|uk|приві́т}}, {{tt|uk|се́рвус}}\n* Urdu: {{tt|ur|سَلام}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{tt|ur|اَلسَّلامُ عَلَیکُم|tr=as-salāmu 'alaikum}} {{qualifier|slightly formal}}, {{tt|ur|سَلام عَلَیکُم}} {{qualifier|common}}, {{tt+|ur|آداب}} {{qualifier|dated or formal}}\n* Uyghur: {{tt|ug|سالام}}\n* Uzbek: {{tt+|uz|salom}}\n* Vietnamese: {{tt+|vi|chào}} (depending on the relationship between speaker and person addressed, one of the following terms may be appended: {{tt+|vi|ông}}, {{tt+|vi|bà}}, {{tt+|vi|cô}}, {{tt+|vi|anh}}, {{tt+|vi|chị}}, {{tt+|vi|em}}, {{tt|vi|quí vị}})\n* Volapük: {{t-check|vo|glidis|alt=glidis!}} {{attention|vo|2=was \"[[glidis]]!\" - assumed inflected form or vocalised spelling; please verify if linking is acceptable. see [[User:So9q/Improved-xte.js/documentation#Translation_fixing]]}}\n* Walloon: {{tt+|wa|a}}, {{tt+|wa|bondjoû}}\n* Welsh: {{tt|cy|siwmae}}\n* Xârâgurè: {{t|axx|vâsgatzo}}\n* Zhuang: {{t-needed|za}}\n}}<!-- close {{multitrans}} -->\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# The word \"hi\" used as a greeting.\n#: {{syn|en|greeting|hello}}\n#: {{ux|en|I didn't even get a '''hi'''.}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{m|en|high}}.\n\n====Adjective====\n{{head|en|adjective}}\n\n# {{informal spelling of|en|high|addl=often in hyphenated terms}}.\n#: {{ux|en|Get '''hi-'''quality videos here!}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|en|hi-score|hi-def|hi-fi|hi-five|hi-hat|hi-lo|Hi-NRG|hi-res|hi-rise|hi-tech|hi-top|hi-vis|hi-way}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|en|lo}}\n* {{l|en|mid}}\n\n===See also===\n{{col2|en|title=etymologically unrelated terms containing the word \"hi\"|hi-rail|hi-wa itck|hi-ya|qui-hi|hi-spy-hi}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=hi|IH}}\n\n{{cln|en|2-letter words|greetings|calculator words}}\n\n==Albanian==\n\n===Etymology===\nTosk form of [[Gheg]] {{m|sq|hî}} (pl. ''hin''), from {{inh|sq|sqj-pro|*skina}}, from {{m|sq|*skines}}, from {{inh|sq|ine-pro|*ḱenHis}} (compare {{cog|la|cinis||dust; cinder}}, {{cog|grc|κόνις||ashes; dust}}).\n\n===Noun===\n{{sq-noun|m||hiri}}\n\n# [[ash]], [[ashes]]\n# [[dust]] of corpses\n# {{lb|sq|figurative}} memory of the dead\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|sq|hirët}}\n* {{l|sq|hirtë}}\n* {{l|sq|hith}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:sq:FMGSH:2026}}\n\n==Antigua and Barbuda Creole English==\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|aig|pronoun}}\n\n# [[he]]\n# [[his]]\n\n==Basque==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|eu|LL-Q8752 (eus)-Aioramu-hi.wav}}\n{{eu-pr}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|eu|pronoun|cat2=personal pronouns|emphatic forms|[[heu]], [[hihaur]], [[herori]]}}\n\n# {{lb|eu|informal|familiar}} {{non-gloss|Second-person singular personal pronoun}}; [[you]]\n\n====Usage notes====\n* This pronoun is very informal, and is only used between close friends or family members. In all other situations, {{m|eu|zu}} is used.\n* When addressing someone using this pronoun, all verb forms (including those not governed by ''hi'') must be in {{w|allocutive agreement}}. For example:\n*: {{uxi|eu|Mahaia handia '''da'''.|The table '''is''' big.}}\n*: {{uxi|eu|Mahaia handia '''duk'''.|The table '''is''' big. (informal, to a male)}}\n*: {{uxi|eu|Mahaia handia '''dun'''.|The table '''is''' big. (informal, to a female)}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{eu-decl-pron}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|eu|hiketa|t=use of ''hi''}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|eu|heu}}\n\n===See also===\n{{eu-personal pronouns}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:eu:EH}}\n* {{R:eu:OEH}}\n\n==Bavarian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|bar|/hiː/}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|bar|gmh|hin}}, {{m|gmh|hine}}, from {{inh|bar|goh|hina}}. Compare {{cog|de|hin}}, {{cog|nl|heen}} and {{cog|en|hence}}.\n\n====Adverb====\n{{bar-adverb}}\n\n# {{senseid|bar|away}}{{ng|Used to denote direction away from the speaker.}}\n#: {{uxi|bar|Wo gehst'n '''hi'''?|Where are you going?}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|bar|dåhi}}\n* {{l|bar|duathi}}\n\n=====See also=====\n{{bar-local adverbs}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nClipping of {{der|bar|gmh|hinüber}}.\n\n====Adjective====\n{{head|bar|adj|predicative}}\n\n# [[out of order]], [[broken]]\n#: {{uxi|bar|Des Auto is '''hi'''.|The car is '''broken'''.}}\n# [[exhausted]], [[depleted]]\n#: {{uxi|bar|Nåchn Spuat gestern woar i afoch nur '''hi'''.|I was just '''exhausted''' after yesterday's sport.}}\n# {{lb|bar|derogatory}} [[dead]], [[deceased]]\n#: {{uxi|bar|Auffigstiegn, owigfoin, '''hi''' gwen.|Ascended, fell off, '''dead'''.}}\n# {{lb|bar|figuratively|derogatory|chiefly|East Central|Vienna}} [[stupid]]\n#: {{syn|bar|ågrennt|deppert|waach}}\n#: {{uxi|bar|Bist '''hi''' in der Marün?|Are you stupid?}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|bar|hinich|hinig}}\n\n==Breton==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|br|cel-pro|*sī}}. Cognate to {{cog|cy|hi}}.\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|br|pronouns|cat2=personal pronouns}}\n\n# [[she]]\n\n===See also===\n{{br-personal pronouns}}\n\n==Catalan==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|ca|roa-oca|y}}, {{m|roa-oca|i}}, {{m|roa-oca|hic}}, from {{inh|ca|la|hīc||here}} and {{m|la|ibī||there}}. Compare {{cog|fr|y}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ca-IPA}}\n* {{homophones|ca|i}}\n* {{rhymes|ca|i}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{ca-ppron|type=encl+procl}}\n\n# ''represents a place associated with the action described by the verb, unless the place would be introduced by the preposition [[de#Catalan|de]]''\n# [[there]] (in constructions such as \"[[there is]]\", \"[[there are]]\", etc.: ''see'' {{l|ca|haver-hi}})\n# ''replaces an adverb (or adverbial phrase) describing the manner, instrument or association of an action''\n# ''replaces a phrase introduced by any preposition except [[de#Catalan|de]] (most commonly [[a/languages A to L#Catalan|a]] or [[en#Catalan|en]])''\n# ''replaces an indefinite noun or an adjective which is the predicate of a verb ''other'' than {{l|ca|ésser}}, {{l|ca|esdevenir}}, [[estar#Catalan|estar]] or [[semblar#Catalan|semblar]]''\n# {{lb|ca|Central Catalan}} ''in combination with other object pronouns, the third-person singular indirect object pronoun'' (\"to him\", \"to her\", \"to it\")\n\n====Usage notes====\n* When more than one object pronoun is associated with a given verb, '''hi''' is always the last in the group.\n* '''Hi''' and [[ho#Catalan|ho]] cannot be used together with the same verb, nor can two '''hi'''s be used together.\n* It is sometimes stated that '''hi''' is ''never'' used to replace a complement beginning with [[de#Catalan|de]]. This is not completely accurate, as '''hi''' can replace ''adverbial'' phrases such as [[de pressa]], [[de sobte]], etc.\n\n====Declension====\n{{ca-personal pronouns}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{sense|Proclitic contractions}} {{l|ca|l'hi}}, {{l|ca|m'hi}}, {{l|ca|n'hi}}, {{l|ca|s'hi}}, {{l|ca|t'hi}}\n* {{sense|Enclitic contractions}} {{l|ca|-ens-hi}}, {{l|ca|-l'hi}}, {{l|ca|-la-hi}}, {{l|ca|-les-hi}}, {{l|ca|-los-hi}}, {{l|ca|'ls-hi}}, {{l|ca|-m'hi}}, {{l|ca|-n'hi}}, {{l|ca|'ns-hi}}, {{l|ca|-s'hi}}, {{l|ca|-t'hi}}, {{l|ca|-us-hi}}, {{l|ca|-vos-hi}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{l|ca|en}} ''pron''\n* {{l|ca|ho}} ''pron''\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:ca:IEC2}}\n\n==Chinese==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{zh-pron\n|c=haai1\n|cat=intj,v\n}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{bor|yue|en|hi}}. {{doublet|zh|嗨}}.\n\n====Interjection====\n{{head|zh|interjection}}\n\n# {{lb|zh|Hong Kong Cantonese}} [[#English|hi]] {{gl|interjection}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{bor|yue|en|hi}}, see {{m|zh|hi auntie}} for more.\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|zh|verb}}\n\n# {{lb|zh|Hong Kong Cantonese|euphemistic|originally|Internet slang|neologism}} {{alt form|yue|屌}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|zh|hi auntie}}\n\n=====See also=====\n* {{l|zh|hihi}}\n* {{zh-l|向左走向右走}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nIrregular romanisation of {{m|yue|揩}}.\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|zh|verb}}\n\n# {{lb|zh|Hong Kong Cantonese}} {{alt form|yue|揩}}\n\n{{cln|zh|greetings}}\n\n==Cornish==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|kw|cel-bry-pro|*hi}}, from {{inh|kw|cel-pro|*sī}}. Cognate with {{cog|br,cy|hi}}, and {{cog|ga|sí}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|kw|hei||RLC}}\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|kw|pronoun|g=f}}\n\n# [[she]] (third-person feminine singular personal pronoun).\n#: {{ux|kw|'''Hi''' a welas.|She saw.}}\n# [[her]] (third-person feminine singular enclitic pronoun, used to reinforce previous pronoun).\n#: {{ux|kw|hy lyver '''hi'''|her book}}\n#: {{ux|kw|Ple eth '''hi'''?|Where did she go?}}\n\n====See also====\n{{kw-personal pronouns}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{non-lemma}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|kw|mutated noun}}\n\n# {{aspirate mutation of|kw|ki}}\n\n==Danish==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{rhymes|da|i}}\n* {{rhymes|da|iː}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{der|da|no|hi}}, from {{der|da|non|hið}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{da-noun|et|er}}\n\n# winter [[quarters]], winter [[lair]] (for hibernation); [[hibernation]] {{q|used literally or figuratively}}\n#: at gå i '''hi'''\n#:: to enter '''hibernation'''\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{da-noun-infl|et|er}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|da|vinterhi}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nOnomatopoeia for laughter or giggling.\n\n====Interjection====\n{{head|da|intj}}\n\n# {{lb|da|onomatopoeia}} {{non-gloss|Signifies giggling.}}\n\n=====See also=====\n* {{l|da|ha}}\n\n==Fasu==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|faa|noun|head=hị}}\n\n# {{lb|faa|Namumi}} {{synonym of|faa|he}}\n\n===References===\n* Karl J. Franklin, ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20160305070551/http://www-01.sil.org/pacific/png/pubs/10745/Comp_Wordlist_Gulfdistrict.pdf Comparative Wordlist 1 of the Gulf District and adjacent areas]'' (1975), page 67\n\n==German==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|de|en|hi}}, from 1990s digitalization.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|de|/ˈhaɪ̯/}}\n* {{audio|de|De-hi.ogg|a=<<Germany>> (<<Berlin>>)}}\n* {{rhymes|de|aɪ̯}}\n* {{homophones|de|hei|high}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|de|interjection}}\n\n# {{tlb|de|very|_|informal}} {{l|en|hi}}\n#: {{syn|de|moin}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:de:DWDS|hi}}\n\n{{cln|de|greetings}}\n\n==Japanese==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{ja-romaji}}\n\n# {{Latn-def|ja|syllable|ひ|ヒ|hi}}\n\n==Kankanaey==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{kne-pr}}\n\n===Article===\n{{kne-head|article}}\n\n# {{dialectal form of|kne|si}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n{{dial syn|kne|si}}\n\n==Latin==\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|la|pronoun form|head=hī}}\n\n# {{inflection of|la|hic||nom|m|p}}\n\n==Maltese==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|mt|ar|هِيَ}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|mt|/iː/}}\n* {{rhymes|mt|iː|s=1}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{mt-pronoun}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|mt|hija}}\n\n====Inflection====\n{{mt-hija}}\n\n==Middle Dutch==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{dercat|dum|gmw-pro|gem-pro|inh=2}}\nFrom {{inh|dum|odt|hīe}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|dum|/hiː/}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|dum|pronoun}}\n\n# [[he]]\n\n====Inflection====\n{{dum-personal pronouns}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|nl|hij|ie}}\n* {{desc|li|hae}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:VMNW|ID34}}\n* {{R:MNW|17185|I}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|enm|pronoun|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|I|t=I|id=I}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|enm|pronoun|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|he|t=he|id=he}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|enm|pronoun|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|heo|t=she|id=she}}\n\n===Etymology 4===\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|enm|pronoun|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|he|t=they|id=they}}\n\n==Middle Low German==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* Possibly: {{IPA|gml|/hiː/}}\n* Certainly: '''[[Wiktionary:About_Middle_Low_German#Stem_vowels|Stem vowel]]: ê⁴'''\n** {{IPA|gml|/hiɛ/|/hiə/}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|gml|pronoun|head=hî}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|gml|hê}}\n\n==Mizo==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|lus|tbq-kuk-pro|*hii}}.\n\n===Determiner===\n{{head|lus|determiner|pronominal|hei|or|he|oblique|hian}}\n\n# [[this]], [[these]] (near the speaker)\n\n====See also====\n{{lus-demonstratives}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:lus:Lorrain}}\n\n==Naga Pidgin==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|nag|hi|ही}}.\n\n===Particle===\n{{head|nag|particle}}\n\n# {{n-g|an [[emphatic]] [[particle]]}}\n\n==Namuyi==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{nmy-IPA}}\n* {{hyph|nmy|hi}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|nmy|noun}}\n\n# [[month]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nmy:Li:2017|page=472}}\n\n==North Frisian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{l|frr|he}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|frr|ofs|hī}}, from {{inh|frr|gmw-pro|*hiʀ}}, from {{inh|frr|gem-pro|*hiz}}, from {{inh|frr|ine-pro|*ḱe}}.\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|frr|pronoun}}\n\n# [[he]]\n#: {{uxi|frr|'''Hi''' wal sin frinjer üüb Feer beschük.|'''He''' wants to visit his relatives on Föhr.}}\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nn|/hiː/}} {{nn-pronu-note}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{der|nn|non|hið}} and {{m|non|híði}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{nn-noun-n1}}\n\n# [[lair]] {{q|of an animal}}, [[sett]] {{q|badgers}}\n#: {{usex|nn|Bjørnane har gått i '''hi''' for vinteren.|The bears have entered their '''lairs''' for the winter.}}\n#: {{ux|nn|Bjørnen søv no, bjørnen søv no i sitt lune '''hi'''|The bear is sleeping now, the bear is sleeping now in his cozy '''lair''' (''a children song'')}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Determiner====\n{{head|nn|determiner form|g=f|masculine|hin|neuter|hitt|plural|hine}}\n\n# {{feminine singular of|nn|hin}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Interjection====\n{{head|nn|interjection}}\n\n# [[hee]]; expression of [[snickering]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nn:OB}}\n\n==Old English==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ang-IPA|hī}}\n* {{rhymes|ang|iː|s=1}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|ang|pronoun|head=hī}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|ang|hīe||they}}\n\n==Old Frisian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{dercat|ofs|ine-pro|inh=1}}\nFrom {{inh|ofs|gmw-pro|*hiʀ}}, from {{inh|ofs|gem-pro|[[*hiz]]}}. Cognates include {{cog|ang|hē}} and {{cog|odt|hie}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|ofs|/ˈhiː/}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|ofs|pronoun|head=hī|g=m|accusative|hine|genitive|sīn|dative|him}}\n\n# {{l|en|he}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{ofs-personal pronouns}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|frr|-}}\n*: Most dialects: {{l|frr|hi}}, {{l|frr|he}}\n*: Halligen: {{l|frr|hii}}\n* {{desc|stq|hie}}\n* {{desc|fy|hy}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:ofs:Bremmer:2009}}\n\n==Old Irish==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n\n====Preposition====\n{{head|sga|prepositions}}\n\n# {{alt sp|sga|i}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Particle====\n{{head|sga|particle}}\n\n# {{alt sp|sga|í}}\n\n==Pali==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n{{pi-alt}}\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|pi|conjunction}}\n\n# [[for]], [[because]]\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|pi|adverb}}\n\n# [[indeed]], [[certainly]]\n\n====References====\n* {{R:pi:Childers}}\n* {{R:pi:PTS}}\n\n==Pirahã==\n\n===Etymology===\nPossibly {{bor+|myp|yrl|i|nocap=1}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|myp|/hɪ̃̀/}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|myp|pronoun}}\n\n# [[he]], [[she]] (third-person subject pronoun)\n# [[him]], [[her]] (third-person object pronoun)\n\n==Sumerian==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{sux-rom}}\n\n# {{romanization of|sux|𒄭|tr=ḫi}}\n\n==Vietnamese==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{vi-IPA}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{vi-verb}}\n\n# to [[bare]] one's [[teeth]]\n#: {{ux|vi|Hi răng ra coi nào.|Come on, show me your teeth.}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|vi|nhe}}\n\n==Waray-Waray==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|war|map-pro|*si}}. Compare {{cog|bcl|si}}, {{cog|ceb|si}}, {{cog|gor|ti}}, {{cog|hil|si}}, {{cog|ilo|si}}, {{cog|pam|i}}, {{cog|pag|si}}, {{cog|tsg|hi}}, and {{cog|war|si}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{war-IPA}}\n\n===Article===\n{{war-head|article}}\n\n# {{n-g|direct marker placed before names or terms of address of people}}\n\n==Welsh==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|cy|/hiː/}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|cy|cel-pro|*sī}} (compare {{cog|sga|sí}}).\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|cy|pronoun|cat2=personal pronouns}}\n\n# [[she]], [[her]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|cy|mutated noun}}\n\n# {{h-prothesis of|cy|i}}\n\n====Mutation====\n{{cy-mut|i}}\n\n==Yilan Creole==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|ycr|ja|-}} {{ja-r|火|ひ|t=fire}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|ycr|/hi/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|ycr|noun}}\n\n# {{lb|ycr|Aohua}} [[fire]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:ycr:Lin 2022}}\n\n{{C|ycr|Fire}}\n\n==Yola==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|yol|h'}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|yol|enm|he|hi|t=they, them}}, from {{inh|yol|ang|hīe}}, {{m|ang|hī}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|yol|/hiː/|/h/}}\n* {{homophones|yol|hea|hie}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|yol|pronoun}}\n\n# [[they]]\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|page=86<ref name=Poole>{{R:Poole 1867}}</ref>\n|chapter=A YOLA ZONG|number=5|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage=Mot w'all aar boust, '''hi''' soon was ee-teight|translation=But with all their bravado '''they''' were soon taught}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|chapter=A YOLA ZONG|number=8|page=86<ref name=Poole>{{R:Poole 1867}}</ref>\n|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage='''Hi''' kinket an keilt, ee vewe aam 'twode snite.|translation='''They''' kicked and rolled, the few that appeared.}}\n# [[them]]\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1927|chapter=ZONG OF TWI MAARKEET MOANS|line=7<ref>{{R:Browne 1927}}</ref>|page=129|title=THE ANCIENT DIALECT OF THE BARONIES OF FORTH AND BARGY, COUNTY WEXFORD|passage=Shu ztaared an shu ztudied '''hi''' near parshagh moan,|translation=She stared and she studied ('''them''') by the other passive woman,}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n==Yoruba==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{yo-IPA|hí}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{yo-pos|noun|hí}}\n\n# {{Latn-def|yo|name|H|h}}\n\n====See also====\n{{list:Latin script letter names/yo}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|yo|sí}}\n\n====Preposition====\n{{yo-pos|preposition|hí}}\n\n# {{lb|yo|Ìkálẹ̀}} [[to]], [[at]], [[toward]] {{q|used when movement is implied}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|yo|húlí|t=to the home}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|yo|ní}}\n\n==Zou==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{zom-IPA|hi}}\n* {{hyph|zom|hi}}\n\n====Particle====\n{{zom-particle|hi}}\n\n# [[yes]]\n# {{n-g|Used to mark a verbal phrase as [[affirmative]].}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|zom|tbq-kuk-pro|*khlii}}.\n\n====Pronunciation 1====\n* {{zom-IPA|hi}}\n* {{hyph|zom|hi}}\n\n=====Noun=====\n{{zom-noun|hi}}\n\n# [[tear]]\n\n====Pronunciation 2====\n* {{zom-IPA|hì}}\n* {{hyph|zom|hi}}\n\n=====Noun=====\n{{zom-noun|hì}}\n\n# [[drop]] {{gl|of water}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:zom:Thanglienmang:2010|page=117}}\n\n{{C|zom|Bodily fluids}}"}}